  <hr style="width: 100%; height: 2px;">

  <p><font size="4"><a name="1tag"></a>1. What does the Institute
  for Life Coach Training (ILCT) do?</font> <a href=
  "faq2.html#TOP"><font size="4">
  <img style="border: 0px solid ; width: 22px; height: 16px;" alt=
  "top" src=
  "top.gif"></font></a></p>

  <p>We are a virtual training school for persons wanting to
  transition into the field of life coaching. Ours is an
  abbreviated course of study targeting those who already have
  experience in people-helping capacities such as psychotherapists,
  professional or pastoral counselors, lay counselors, 12-step
  group facilitators, and similar service providers.</p>

  <p><font size="4"><a name="2tag"></a>2. How are the classes
  taught?</font> <a href=
  "faq2.html#TOP"><font size="4">
  <img style="border: 0px solid ; width: 22px; height: 16px;" alt=
  "top" src=
  "top.gif"></font></a></p>

  <p>All of our classes are taught via telephone using the latest
  technology to link up students throughout the world by
  telebridge. No special equipment is required; you simply dial a
  regular long-distance number and a computer hooks you up to our
  virtual classroom. Two professional coaches facilitate each class
  using a combination of lecture, class discussion, and live
  coaching.</p>

  <p>Readings for each class are assigned from two texts and
  homework assignments are provided in a 400+ page Training
  Curriculum. Each student is paired with another person from the
  class and they are assigned to meet weekly by phone to discuss
  integration of the material and try out new skills by
  practice-coaching each other.</p>

  <p class="western" style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p>

  <p><font size="4"><a name="3tag"></a>3. What is the
  benefit of receiving formal training in life
  coaching?</font> <font><font size="4"><a href=
  "faq2.html#TOP"><img style="border: 0px solid ; width: 22px; height: 16px;"
       alt="top" src=
       "top.gif"></a></font></font></p>

  <p>Although formal training is not yet required to practice life
  coaching, it is our firm belief that those who have been trained
  through a recognized institution are generally more skilled and
  professional in their service delivery. Coaching draws upon
  numerous disciplines and yet is a distinct profession. Our
  training clarifies these distinctions, covers the skills of
  effective coaching, addresses business development and marketing
  of a coaching business, and invites students to carefully examine
  their own lives to ensure alignment with coaching principles of a
  personal life vision, mission and purpose.</p>

  <p>Additionally, formal training aids the public in making an
  informed decision about selection of a coach, as they look to
  schooling and certification as marks of credibility.</p>

  <p class="western" style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p>

  <p><font size="4"><a name="4tag"></a>4. Are there any
  prerequisites for becoming a student in the ILCT?</font>
  <font><font size="4"><a href=
  "faq2.html#TOP"><img style="border: 0px solid ; width: 22px; height: 16px;"
       alt="top" src=
       "top.gif"></a></font></font></p>

  <p>No. However, because this is an accelerated program (five
  months, as contrasted with some programs lasting 12 months or
  more), we recommend that students have a fairly good base of
  training and experience in people-helping roles. We assume
  participants have a solid understanding of active listening
  skills, ability to quickly establish trust and rapport, and good
  awareness of their use of &lsquo;self&rsquo; within a designed
  relationship.</p>

  <p class="western" style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p>

  <p><font size="4"><a name="5tag"></a>5. What does a person
  get upon completion of the program?</font>
  <font><font size="4"><a href=
  "faq2.html#TOP"><img style="border: 0px solid ; width: 22px; height: 16px;"
       alt="top" src=
       "top.gif"></a></font></font></p>

  <p>Graduates receive a certificate verifying completion of the
  training and are able to download an icon for use on websites and
  other promotional material that identifies them as a graduate of
  the Institute for Life Coach Training.</p>

  <p class="western" style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p>

  <p><font size="4"><a name="6tag"></a>6. Why does ILCT have
  a Christian Track?</font> <font><font size=
  "4"><a href=
  "faq2.html#TOP"><img style="border: 0px solid ; width: 22px; height: 16px;"
       alt="top" src=
       "top.gif"></a></font></font></p>

  <p>Life coaching is about examining the entirety of a
  person&rsquo;s life; their core values, sense of life purpose or
  calling, and the fulfillment of that calling on every plane of
  their being. In as much as this includes examination of
  one&rsquo;s spirituality and theological beliefs, Christians
  often prefer to train under facilitators who ascribe to their
  same core beliefs.</p>

  <p>Likewise, many Christians seeking to hire a coach prefer that
  he or she holds their same convictions and works within a
  Christian worldview and value system. For those who desire
  training from a distinctly Christian perspective, we offer this
  unique track &ndash; the first of its kind. ILCT has trained more
  Christian coaches than any other professional program in the
  world.</p>

  <p class="western" style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p>

  <p><font size="4"><a name="7tag"></a>7. What makes the
  Christian Track different from the regular track?</font>
  <font><font size="4"><a href=
  "faq2.html#TOP"><img style="border: 0px solid ; width: 22px; height: 16px;"
       alt="top" src=
       "top.gif"></a></font></font></p>

  <p>The classes are facilitated from a distinctly Christian
  perspective by our Director, Christopher McCluskey, and Judy
  Santos, President of the Christian Coaches Network. Their
  theological framework is nondenominational, fairly conservative,
  and evangelical. Chris and Judy are both fulltime practicing
  coaches who work from a model similar to that presented in
  <u>Christian Coaching</u> (Navpress) by Dr. Gary R. Collins (this
  book can be found at your Christian bookstore or purchased online
  at <font color=
  "#0000FF"><u>www.christian-living.com)</u></font>.</p>

  <p>All of the basic coaching skills, business development,
  marketing techniques, and self-examination covered in the regular
  track are also covered in the Christian track. The format of the
  classes, assigned texts, and curriculum guide are the same. Each
  class begins with a prayer for the Holy Spirit&rsquo;s guidance
  and five minutes of mutual encouragement, sharing praises for
  God&rsquo;s blessings through the learning and the development of
  students&rsquo; businesses. Coaching principles from the readings
  are examined in view of Scripture and a framework for a
  distinctly Christian approach to coaching is developed.</p>

  <p>Most of the skills and principles of professional coaching are
  immediately transferable to a Christian model of practice. Some
  of the foundational assumptions, however, are quite different.
  For example, page 9 of the ILCT Curriculum Guide states, &ldquo;I
  strongly believe that we are all the creator and director of our
  own life drama, able to create &lsquo;on purpose&rsquo; what your
  life will look like, feel like, and be like. It is your
  opportunity and responsibility to write the script, be the
  producer and director and to gather the other characters in your
  life drama.&rdquo;</p>

  <p>By contrast, a core assumption of the Christian Track is
  summed up clearly by Tom Paterson in his book <u>Living the Life
  You Were Meant to Live</u> (Nelson): &ldquo;A Life Plan is
  <i>God&rsquo;s</i> plan for your life. It is not a plan that you
  conceive and develop, but a plan that you <i>discover</i> through
  a series of helpful exercises and processes&rdquo; (p. 7 &ndash;
  emphasis added). These differing foundational assumptions can
  have a dramatic impact on the coaching alliance and the spirit in
  which the work of coaching is done.</p>

  <p class="western" style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p>

  <p><font size="4"><a name="8tag"></a>8. Do graduates of
  the Christian Track have the same credibility as the regular
  track?</font> <font><font size="4"><a href=
  "faq2.html#TOP"><img style="border: 0px solid ; width: 22px; height: 16px;"
       alt="top" src=
       "top.gif"></a></font></font></p>

  <p>Absolutely. Neither the ILCT nor the International Coach
  Federation (ICF) draws any distinction between graduates of
  either track. Graduates of the Christian track even have the
  option of receiving a certificate that does not specify which
  track they completed, if they so desire. (Some prefer this if
  they plan to service both Christian and secular markets.)</p>

  <p class="western" style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p>

  <p><font size="4"><a name="9tag"></a>9. I&rsquo;ve heard
  that once a training program is completed, people can go on to
  become <i>certified</i> in coaching. Can graduates of ILCT become
  certified?</font> <font><font size="4"><a href=
  "faq2.html#TOP"><img style="border: 0px solid ; width: 22px; height: 16px;"
       alt="top" src=
       "top.gif"></a></font></font></p>

  <p>Yes. There are several coaching certifications available. All
  ILCT graduates receive <u>40</u> hours of coach-specific
  training, which count towards the education hours required for
  numerous certification programs including those of the
  International Coach Federation (ICF). Our program is accredited
  by the ICF.</p>

  <p>ILCT also offers a certification of our own &ndash; the
  Certified Life Coach (CLC) designation. For information on this,
  contact Edwina Adams at 972-867-1915 or via email at <font color=
  "#0000FF"><u><a href=
  "mailto:edwina@lifecoachtraining.com">edwina@lifecoachtraining.com</a></u></font>.</p>

  <p class="western" style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p>

  <p><font size="4"><a name="10tag"></a>10. When do classes
  meet?</font> <font><font size="4"><a href=
  "faq2.html#TOP"><img style="border: 0px solid ; width: 22px; height: 16px;"
       alt="top" src=
       "top.gif"></a></font></font></p>

  <p>The Christian Track meets for one hour on Mondays and
  Wednesdays at 2:00 PM Eastern Standard Time. The Spring classes
  begin March 22<sup>nd</sup> 2004.</p>

  <p class="western" style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p>

  <p><font size="4"><a name="11tag"></a>11. What is the cost
  of the program?</font> <font><font size=
  "4"><a href=
  "faq2.html#TOP"><img style="border: 0px solid ; width: 22px; height: 16px;"
       alt="top" src=
       "top.gif"></a></font></font></p>

  <p>Tuition for the Basic Training Program (whether Christian or
  regular track) is $1,995 US plus books (roughly $95 US).</p>

  <p class="western" style="margin-bottom: 0in;">&nbsp;</p>

  <p><font size="4"><a name="12tag"></a>12. How does a
